I would start to dislike the things I have like clothing and furniture and then I would replace that stuff again and again. I can't chose what I want to like anymore, it's tearing apart my life.

snippet.textDisplay:
I think I might have DID or something like it. I have other I guess, personalities or people. They don't really take control often. But I can give your their names :D

Evelyn- She's 6 or 7 and is a hyper child,
Acorn- She takes care of Evelyn and is 16 or so
Ghost- She is very shy and usually says small things, 20 or so years old
Mekena- She is the insane one I guess, she is a protector of sorts. She also has anger issues. She is about 18 years old
Mark- He is the boy of the group, he always want to wear sweat pants lol. He is chill and helps me calm down. 23 for sure.
Seashell- She is the 'normal' one, for say. Around 14, she helps me with drama and friend stuff.
Merida- She is Seashells mother, 30 or so. She helps me with myc classes, mostly math.
Pandora- She is like really old, idk exact age but around 2,000. She takes care of everyone and makes sure none of us are getting in trouble.

I love all of them dearly and wouldn't trade them for anything!

snippet.textDisplay:
So, I'm currently seeking my masters in Psychology and am about a year away from graduation. I'm researching for a paper on DID, its symptoms, treatments, and whether or not it is a defense mechanism, a chemical restructure of the brain due to trauma, or a combination of both.


For me, the validity of DID in regards to client experience, alter amnesia, and transition are fully there. I do not have doubts about the disorder itself or the clients and their stories. However, what I have discovered is that DID is treated differently than most other disorders. The most widely used form of therapy in regards to mental disorders is Cognitive Behavioral Therapy accompanied by immersion therapy. However, for the cases of DID that I've seen, therapeutic approaches are centered around symptoms rather than underlying meaning for the brain to develop the disorder. Rather than immersion being focused on traumatic events that the alters are protecting others from, we almost give focus to the alters themselves. While I feel that this is happening because DID is still being examined, I almost feel that we are being dishonest with our clients in telling them that responsibility for ones actions while they are in an altered state does not lie on anyone but that alter. The reason I have issues with this is because, if we had a, let's say, serial killer with DID, who do we put the blame on? Who do we punish? How can we administer justice? We don't look at someone with antisocial personality disorder and tell them that while rage, lack of empathy, and altered state of mind are symptoms of their disorder; these symptoms do not take away from their responsibility of their actions.


I think that because we are still searching for effective treatment and therapy, we aren't truly helping clients with DID. We are almost telling them, "Well, this is your life. This is your state of being. I don't really know how to treat it. So, let's instead get you accompanied and used to it so that you don't suffer." And, if that is the case, is it wrong? I'm not sure yet. My studies and research of DID always leads me to more questions than answers.
